"It's not about perfection. What's a perfect painting? What's interesting about a perfect painting?" -Peter Doig
The rising moon above the Atlantic Ocean ominously illuminates three figures in a Caribbean landscape. A composition inspired by a view from beyond the artist‚Äôs house in Trinidad, the two trees frame men stilled on the verge of catastrophe as a mysterious scene unfolds. A hockey player with spectral pallor and camouflage jersey confronts the central, inward looking figure with a bent head, while another man with a flowing top knot and a harlequin shirt holds a handy-cam, filming the scene as both voyeur and visual scribe. Doig‚Äôs compositions are redolent with art historical references, from the allegorical landscapes of Peter Brueghel to the figures of Edvard Munch. The relationship between the figures gesture towards incipient violence as a modern condition, and the dilemmas inherent in recording vexed and intertwined histories.

Cape Cod Morning, 1950 @fondationbeyeler! Here are some famous quotes by #EdwardHopper:
Great art is the outward expression of an inner life in the artist, and this inner life will result in his personal vision of the world.

I find in working always the disturbing intrusion of elements not a part of my most interested vision, and the inevitable obliteration and replacement of this vision by the work itself as it proceeds.

I trust Winsor and Newton and I paint directly upon it.

If the technical innovations of the Impressionists led merely to a more accurate representation of nature, it was perhaps of not much value in enlarging their powers of expression.

In general it can be said that a nation's art is greatest when it most reflects the character of its people.

In its most limited sense, modern, art would seem to concern itself only with the technical innovations of the period.

It's to paint directly on the canvas without any funny business, as it were, and I use almost pure turpentine to start with, adding oil as I go along until the medium becomes pure oil. I use as little oil as I can possibly help, and that's my method.

My aim in painting has always been the most exact transcription possible of my most intimate impression of nature.

No amount of skillful invention can replace the essential element of imagination.

Painting will have to deal more fully and less obliquely with life and nature's phenomena before it can again become great.

The question of the value of nationality in art is perhaps unsolvable.

The trend in some of the contemporary movements in art, but by no means all, seems to deny this ideal and to me appears to lead to a purely decorative conception of painting.

There will be, I think, an attempt to grasp again the surprise and accidents of nature and a more intimate and sympathetic study of its moods, together with a renewed wonder and humility on the part of such as are still capable of these basic reactions.
.

Warhol on #love: 12 quotes. Happy #ValentinesDay!
According to Andy:
1. ‚ÄúPeople should fall in love with their eyes closed. Just close your eyes. Don‚Äôt look.‚Äù
2. ‚ÄúWhen people are ready to, they change. They never do it before then, and sometimes they die before they get around to it. You can‚Äôt make them change if they don‚Äôt want to, just like when they do want to, you can‚Äôt stop them.‚Äù
3. ‚ÄúAs soon as you stop wanting something, you get it.‚Äù
4. ‚ÄúI wonder if it‚Äôs possible to have a love affair that lasts forever.‚Äù
5. ‚ÄúI think everybody should be nice to everybody.‚Äù
6. ‚ÄúBrigitte Bardot was one of the first women to be really modern and treat men like love objects, buying them and discarding them. I like that.‚Äù
7. ‚ÄúA friend of mine always says, ‚ÄòWomen love me for the man I‚Äôm not.‚Äô‚Äù
8. ‚ÄúEvery time I have a ‚Äòromance‚Äô I‚Äôm so nervous I bring the whole office with me‚Ä¶ They all come to pick me up and then we go to pick her up. Love me, love my office.‚Äù
9. ‚ÄúI always run into strong women who are looking for weak men to dominate them.‚Äù
10. ‚ÄúSome people think that violence is sexy, but I could never see that.‚Äù
11. ‚ÄúMost of the people in offices are actually getting paid while they day-dream up their new seductions.‚Äù
12. ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know anybody who doesn‚Äôt have a fantasy. Everybody must have a fantasy.‚Äù
Source: The Philosophy of Andy Warhol (From A to B and Back Again) / Warhol @christies
